American crony capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury and its IMF allies blamed the problems in this region on crony capitalism, lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American-style accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of their own entrepreneurs, East Asia developed faster than any other region—and with greater stability—over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be perfect to criticize others."
Enron used large accounting schemes and complex financial products (derivatives) to deceive investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to gain influence and power, shaping U.S. energy policy and evading regulations.
Crony capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of a single party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, allegedly tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial dispute in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the accounting standards-setting body, supposedly independent, tried to clean up the accounting of top executives' deals.
It was partly because of him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was obstructed.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is just a thin veneer for the benefit of old companies: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and the problems were not revealed demonstrates the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it demonstrates the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to take a closer look at Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Contributions to campaigns were not simply matters of public interest, but constituted an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be learned from this company.
Some relate to politics: the Enron scandal strengthens the arguments in favor of campaign financing reform and the necessity for even more effective laws that will have to be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests that in fact can buy elections.
The Bush administration refuses, however, to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons relate to economics, particularly information economics.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals that aim to efficiently allocate resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The control of accounts is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guards?
Who will control the account controllers?
We count greatly on motivations.
Audit committees desire to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and accounting control raises other perverse motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, recognized the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the forgotten hero of the collapse.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients—nothing surprising, given the collusion that developed—strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood—and the Enron collapse so clearly showed—is that motivations are important, but that unregulated markets cannot themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron was implementing.
The new economy - and its new complicated financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to obscure.
Instead of facing the problems, the business America systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American crony capitalism.
The major problem of our time is to find the right balance between government and market.
The status quo will claim that Enron was an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors claim that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information they receive sufficiently reflects the economic situation of a company.
Under the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people around the world say nothing about the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we see that they can manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new venues for abuse are created time and again—take the U.S. repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly seen the consequences of the excesses of unfettered market liberalization.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge to meet is to achieve the right balance.
